Node.Notes: Uncertain. "Silence is praise to you in Zion, O God" makes little sense to most, so many follow ancient versions "it is fitting" by revocalizing MT to "to be like/equal to," extended to mean "to be due/fitting." Tree assumes "Silent praise belongs to you in Zion, O God."
Interpreting silence which is praise (NpNp) as silent praise (whatever practice it may refer to)
Assuming a relative clause without relative particle and relative clause functions as S.
Many take as "your holy temple" despite unusual syntax. Tree assumes "the goodness of your house" and "the holiness of your temple" in apposition.
Peculiar in that long a is retained, though word has to be construct here (among 13 words discussed in Masora as retaining long a in construct state).

Node.English: you call forth songs of joy

Node.Notes: Literally, "outgoings of the morning and the evening," which seems to refer to one end of the earth to the other (and thus the people of the whole earth). Some take it literally as God makes the dawn and the evening shout for joy.
